      <hedline>
        <hl1>Now Playing: Hollywood vs. the Internet</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dean Baker letter responds to Motion Picture Assn chmn Jack Valenti's June 21 Op-Ed article on copyright protection; proposes individual tax credit to support creative and artistic work, as alternative to copyright protection</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Jack Valenti, chairman of the Motion Picture Association, asks, ''If copyright can no longer protect the distribution of the work they produce, who will invest immense sums to create films or any other creative material of the kind we now take for granted?'' (Op-Ed, June 21).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Jack Valenti, chairman of the Motion Picture Association, asks, ''If copyright can no longer protect the distribution of the work they produce, who will invest immense sums to create films or any other creative material of the kind we now take for granted?'' (Op-Ed, June 21).</p>
        <p>There are many ways other than copyrights to support creative and artistic work. Just to give one example, the country could establish an individual tax credit dedicated for this purpose. Such a tax credit would be a much less serious government intervention in the market than arresting people for possessing software that reproduces copyrighted material.</p>
        <p>DEAN BAKER  Washington, June 21, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is co-director, Center for Economic and Policy Research.</p>
      </block>
